{"title_page": "Muslim Makwana", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\nThe '''Makwana''' [[Muslims]] are Muslim converts from the Makwana [[Kshatriya]] [[Kolis|Koli]] and [[Rajput]] community.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7tAOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA190&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=An Anglo-Indian Dictionary: A Glossary of Indian Terms Used in English, and of Such English Or Other Non-Indian Terms as Have Obtained Special Meanings in India|last=Whitworth|first=George Clifford|date=1885|publisher=K. Paul, Trench|language=en}}</ref> According to their traditions, their ancestor Bapuji, the son of Harpal Makwana, converted to [[Islam]]. He founded to the principality of Lalpur-Mandva, in [[Mahikantha]]. \n\nThe Makwana Kolis ruled several [[Princely state|Princely states]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_r4MAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA427&dq=Makvana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makvana%20Koli&f=false|title=Gazetteer|last=State)|first=Bombay (India|date=1880|publisher=Printed at the Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n* [[Mayur Rajesh Makwana]]\n* [[Ramas State|Ramas]]\n* [[Prempur]]\n* [[Kadoli State|Kadoli]]\n* [[Khedwada|Khervada]]\n* [[Derol]]\n* [[Tajpuri State|Tajpuri]]\n* [[Vakhtapur (Mahi Kantha)|Vakhtapur]]\n* [[Hapa State|Hapa]]\n* [[Dedhrota]]\n* [[Likhi State|Likhi]]\n* [[Gabat State|Gabat]]\n* [[Maguna]]\n* [[Tejpura State|Tejpura]]\n* [[Memadpura|Memadpur]]\n* [[Deloli]]\n* [[Kasalpura]]\n* [[Virsoda]]\n* [[Palej State|Palej]]\n* [[Rampura State|Rampura]]\n* [[Ijpura]]\n* [[Ranipura]].\n\nThe Makwana are now mainly small peasant proprietors found in north [[Gujarat]]. They are [[Sunni]] Muslims and speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]. The Makwana intermarry with other [[Muslim Rajput]] groups in the neighbourhood, such as the [[Molesalam Rajput|Molesalam]], [[Muslim Nayak|Nayak]] and [[Muslim Parmar (Gujarat)|Parmar]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gSZqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=Genealogy, Archive, Image: Interpreting Dynastic History in Western India, c. 1090-2016|last=Jhala|first=Jayasinhji|date=2018-07-19|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=9783110601299|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NYK7ZSpPzkUC&pg=PA37&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=The Rajputs of Saurashtra|last=Singhji|first=Virbhadra|date=1994|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=9788171545469|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GDRWAglUumEC&pg=PA71&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=Kings and Untouchables: A Study of the Caste System in Western India|last=Perez|first=Rosa Maria|date=2004|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=9788180280146|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4Cy_-FXW9BQC&pg=PA717&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=Gujarat|date=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=9788179911044|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=c70MAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA140&dq=Makvana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makvana%20Koli&f=false|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency ...|last=State)|first=Bombay (India|date=1884|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gSZqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Genealogy, Archive, Image: Interpreting Dynastic History in Western India, c. 1090-2016|last=Jhala|first=Jayasinhji|date=2018-07-19|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=9783110601299|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Indian Muslim}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n{{India-ethno-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\nThe '''Makwana''' [[Muslims]] are a community in India.\n\nThe Makwana are now mainly small peasant proprietors found in north [[Gujarat]]. They are [[Sunni]] Muslims and speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]. The Makwana intermarry with other [[Muslim Rajput]] groups in the neighbourhood, such as the [[Molesalam Rajput|Molesalam]], [[Muslim Nayak|Nayak]] and [[Muslim Parmar (Gujarat)|Parmar]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gSZqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=Genealogy, Archive, Image: Interpreting Dynastic History in Western India, c. 1090-2016|last=Jhala|first=Jayasinhji|date=2018-07-19|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=9783110601299|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GDRWAglUumEC&pg=PA71&dq=Makwana+Koli#v=onepage&q=Makwana%20Koli&f=false|title=Kings and Untouchables: A Study of the Caste System in Western India|last=Perez|first=Rosa Maria|date=2004|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=9788180280146|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Indian Muslim}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n{{India-ethno-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ramhet Mahaur", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_Makwana"}
